FUSARIUM HEAD BLIGHT, WHEAT - CANADA: (ALBERTA) SPREAD
******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 16 Jan 2015
Source: Alberta Farmer [edited]
http://www.albertafarmexpress.ca/2015/01/16/fusarium-on-the-march-and-wreaking-havoc/


Fusarium on the march and wreaking havoc
----------------------------------------
Once limited to wheat fields in southern Alberta, fusarium head blight is spreading quickly into central Alberta and beyond. "Over the past few years, (fusarium) has increased considerably," said Trevor Blois, 20/20 Seed Labs. "This year [2014], around 16 percent of samples are testing positive." In 2007, only one percent of samples sent to his lab tested positive for fusarium. That figure jumped to 9 percent in 2012 and 13 percent for [2013].

But the news gets worse -- the disease has spread to areas where it's never been seen before. "In 2007, it was pretty much restricted to 5 counties in southern Alberta," said Blois, adding it's now becoming common in central and northern Alberta. "Right now, 57 percent of counties that we test seed in are testing positive. It's quite widespread."

"_Fusarium graminearum_ causes the most severe losses, but we are seeing the highest levels of other fusarium species as well," said Blois, adding those species can cause seedling blight, root rot, and crown rot in other crops as well and also produce harmful mycotoxins.

This sudden rise in fusarium in Alberta has been caused, in part, by tighter rotations, a shift toward zero-tillage farming, and "a general increase in the inoculum." Environmental conditions also need to be right. An [increase] in corn [maize] acres has also played a role. "It will probably survive for a couple of years in the corn stubble."

But the biggest issue is infected seed. "One of the most important things is testing your seed and ensuring that you're using clean seed," said Blois. "There's a lot of planting of infected seed."

Losses in Canada from fusarium head blight have ranged between CAD 50 million and CAD 300 million [about USD 41.4 million USD 248 million] and annually since the early 1990s, when fusarium outbreaks began in Eastern Canada.

[Byline: Jennifer Blair]

