Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Several fungal species originally classed into the genus _Fusarium_ can affect wheat and other cereals causing foot rot, seedling blight, and head blight symptoms. The pathogens form a complex of diseases on seeds, seedlings and adult plants. Current names of the fungi include _Gibberella zeae_ (previously _Fusarium graminearum_), _Fusarium poae_, _Monographella nivalis_ var. _nivalis_ (previously _Fusarium_ or _Microdochium nivale_), and _Microdochium majus_.

The diseases are generally favoured by humid conditions, and stress factors may increase plant susceptibility. Besides dramatically reducing yield and quality, the grain may also become contaminated with fungal toxins (mycotoxins). The fungi persist and multiply on infected crop residues, spores are spread by wind, water, mechanical means, and with infected plant material (including seeds). For seedling blights, the main pathogen source is contaminated seed. Disease management includes fungicides as crop sprays or seed treatments, long crop rotations with non-hosts, and planting of cereal varieties with reduced susceptibility. Use of certified clean seeds, as mentioned above, is essential.

New fungal strains are emerging worldwide. Re-emergence of some fusarium diseases thought to be driven mainly by changes to climate and agronomic practices has been reported from the UK (ProMED-mail post 20100726.2497). In Canada, the emergence of a new FHB strain with increased mycotoxin levels has been reported in 2009 (ProMED-mail post 20091210.4211).

